  "local_port": 55500,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some English grammar tricks that I could learn in next 20 minutes?",
  "response": "Here are some quick English grammar tricks you can learn in the next 20 minutes:\n\n1. **Subject-Verb Agreement**: Ensure that your subjects and verbs agree in number. Remember:\n   - Singular subject \u2192 singular verb (e.g., \"The dog barks.\")\n   - Plural subject \u2192 plural verb (e.g., \"The dogs bark.\")\n\n2. **Commonly Confused Words**:\n   - **Their vs. There vs. They\u2019re**: \n     - Their: possessive form (e.g., \"Their house is big.\")\n     - There: refers to a place (e.g., \"The book is over there.\")\n     - They\u2019re: contraction for \"they are\" (e.g., \"They\u2019re going to the park.\")\n   - **Your vs. You\u2019re**:\n     - Your: possessive form (e.g., \"Is this your book?\")\n     - You\u2019re: contraction for \"you are\" (e.g., \"You\u2019re very kind.\")\n\n3. **Comma Usage**:\n   - Use commas before conjunctions (and, but, or) in compound sentences (e.g., \"I wanted to go, but I was too tired.\")\n   - Use commas to separate items in a list (e.g., \"I bought apples, oranges, and bananas.\")\n   - Use commas after introductory phrases (e.g., \"After dinner, we went for a walk.\")\n\n4. **The Oxford Comma**: When listing three or more items, consider using the Oxford comma for clarity (e.g., \"I love my parents, Lady Gaga, and Oprah.\" Without it, it could imply a different meaning.)\n\n5. **Active vs. Passive Voice**:\n   - Active Voice: The subject performs the action (e.g., \"The chef cooked the meal.\")\n   - Passive Voice: The subject receives the action (e.g., \"The meal was cooked by the chef.\")\n   Aim to use active voice for more engaging writing.\n\n6. **The Rule of Three**: When writing lists or descriptions, using three items can create a rhythm and make your writing more persuasive (e.g., \"Our services are quick, efficient, and affordable.\")\n\n7. **Using Semicolons**: Use semicolons to connect closely related independent clauses (e.g., \"I have a big exam tomorrow; I can't go out tonight.\"). This can help reduce the number of sentences and create more complex structures.\n\n8. **Pronoun Reference**: Ensure pronouns (he, she, it, they) clearly refer to a noun (antecedent). Ambiguity can confuse the reader (e.g., Instead of saying \"When Sarah met Jennifer, she was excited,\" specify who \"she\" refers to: \"When Sarah met Jennifer, Sarah was excited.\")\n\n9. **Avoid Dangling Modifiers**: Ensure that introductory phrases clearly refer to the intended subject (e.g., \"Running to the bus, my backpack fell off\" is unclear. Correct it to \"Running to the bus, I dropped my backpack.\")\n\n10. **Tense Consistency**: Keep the same tense throughout your writing unless there's a reason to change it (e.g., \"She walks to the store and buys apples\" is consistent vs. \"She walks to the store and bought apples,\" which mixes tenses).\n\nSpend a few minutes practicing these tricks, and then try to apply them while writing a short paragraph to reinforce your learning!",
